Generative Deep Learning¶

Note: For the walk-through of Variational Autoencoders (VAEs), go to the last section of the MNIST notebook.

1. Text Generation with LSTMs¶

We first train an LSTM so that it's able to predict the next token (or next few tokens) in a sequence using an initial string of text (called the conditioning data). We then update the input to include the predicted text and predict the token after. By stringing these predicted tokens together, we generate a text sequence.

The predictions of the LSTM are a discrete probability distribution over all tokens. We can sample from a closely-related sampling distribution which is characterized by temperature.

def reweight_distribution(original_distribution, temperature=0.5):
    distribution = np.log(original_distribution) / temperature
    distribution = np.exp(distribution)
    return distribution / np.sum(distribution)

When temperature = 0, the text generator will always return the most likely token. This will result in text that has very little entropy but is not very interesting. As the temperature goes higher, the text becomes more interesting, but it becomes more likely that the text stops making sense or does not follow the norms of the English language.

We shall train our model on the texts of Nietzsche.

We now extract partially overlapping sequences of length maxlen. The sequneces are then one-hot encoded and packed into a Numpy array (shape (sequences, maxlen, unique_characters)). In addition, we prepare an array y that contain the one-hot-encoded characters that come after each extracted sequence.

In [3]:
maxlen = 60  # sequence of 60 characters
step = 3  # controls the amount of overlap between successive sampled sequences

sentences = []  # stores the extracted sequences
next_chars = []  # stores the targets
for i in range(0, len(text) - maxlen, step):
    sentences.append(text[i:(i + maxlen)])
    next_chars.append(text[i + maxlen])
    
print('Number of sentences:', len(sentences))

chars = sorted(list(set(text)))  # list of unique characters in the corpus
print('Number of unique characters:', len(chars))
char_indices = dict((char, chars.index(char)) for char in chars)  # dict maps tokens to their index in 'chars'

print('One hot encoding...')
x = np.zeros((len(sentences), maxlen, len(chars)), dtype=np.bool)
y = np.zeros((len(sentences), len(chars)), dtype=np.bool)
for i, sentence in enumerate(sentences):
    for t, char in enumerate(sentence):
        x[i, t,char_indices[char]] = 1
    y[i, char_indices[next_chars[i]]] = 1
    
print('Finished!')

As the targets are one hot encoded, we use categorical_crossentropy as the loss.

In [5]:
optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.01)
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer)

Let us develop a function that reweights the original probability distribution from the model according to a chosen temperature.

In [6]:
def sample(preds, temperature=1.0):
    preds = np.asarray(preds).astype('float64')
    preds = np.log(preds) / temperature
    exp_preds = np.exp(preds)
    preds = exp_preds / np.sum(exp_preds)
    probas = np.random.multinomial(1, preds, 1)
    return np.argmax(probas)

As the fitted probability distribution evolves with the epochs, we can use it to create an evolving, re-weighted probability distribution for sampling characters. We fit the model and generate a text at each epoch.

In [7]:
for epoch in range(1, 60):
    print('epoch', epoch)
    model.fit(x, y, batch_size=128, epochs=1)  # fits the model for one iteraton of the data
        
    if epoch in [19, 59]:

        # we randomly select the conditioning data (or string) use to initialize the generated text
        start_index = random.randint(0, len(text) - maxlen - 1)  
        generated_text = text[start_index:(start_index + maxlen)]
        print('--- Generating with seed: "' + generated_text + '"')
        
        for temperature in [0.2, 0.5, 1.0]:
            print('------ temperature: ', temperature)
            sys.stdout.write(generated_text)
        
            # generate 400 characters from the seed text
            for i in range(400):
            
                # one-hot encode the generated_text
                sampled = np.zeros((1, maxlen, len(chars)))
                for t, char in enumerate(generated_text):
                    sampled[0, t, char_indices[char]] = 1
            
                # sample the next character given the generated_text
                preds = model.predict(sampled, verbose=0)[0]
                next_index = sample(preds, temperature)
                next_char = chars[next_index]
            
                generated_text += next_char  # append predicted char to text segment
                generated_text = generated_text[1:]  # ... and trim of the last segment
            
                sys.stdout.write(next_char)

2. DeepDream¶

Recall we visualized filters by performing gradient ascent on the input of the covnet. The loss is chosen specifically so that the algorithm maximizes the activation of a chosen covnet filter. DeepDream is very similar, though it has a few differences:

  • we maximimize the activation of entire layers (rather than a specific filter)
  • we start from an exising image, causing the algorithm to distort elements of the image in an artistic fashion. In contrast, the feature visualization approach started with a noisy input.
  • the input images are processed at different scales (called octaces), which improves the quality of the images.

We'll use the inception_v3 model to produce visualizations

In [8]:
from keras.applications import inception_v3
from keras import backend as K

K.set_learning_phase(0)  # disables trainings
model = inception_v3.InceptionV3(weights='imagenet', include_top=False)  # exclude the classier on top

We can then define a loss. We'll maximize the weighted sum of the L2 norm of the activations of a set of high-level layers.

In [9]:
layer_contributions = {'mixed2': 0.2, 'mixed3': 3., 'mixed4': 2., 'mixed5': 1.5}

layer_dict = dict([(layer.name, layer) for layer in model.layers])  # dict maps layer names to instances

# define the loss as the weighting of the specified layer's activations
loss = K.variable(0.)
for layer_name in layer_contributions:
    coeff = layer_contributions[layer_name]
    activation = layer_dict[layer_name].output
    
    scaling = K.prod(K.cast(K.shape(activation), 'float32'))
    loss = loss + coeff * K.sum(K.square(activation[:, 2: -2, 2: -2, :])) / scaling

We can then implement gradient ascent on this loss.

In [10]:
dream = model.input  # will hold the generated image

grads = K.gradients(loss, dream)[0]  # calculates the gradient of dream wrt loss
grads /= K.maximum(K.mean(K.abs(grads)), 1e-7)  # normalizes the gradient

outputs = [loss, grads]
fetch_loss_and_grads = K.function([dream], outputs)  # define function to retrieve outputs given an input

def eval_loss_and_grads(x):
    outs = fetch_loss_and_grads([x])
    loss_value = outs[0]
    grad_values = outs[1]
    return loss_value, grad_values

def gradient_ascent(x, iterations, step, max_loss=None):
    for i in range(iterations):
        loss_value, grad_values = eval_loss_and_grads(x)
        if max_loss is not None and loss_value > max_loss:
            break
        print('... Loss value at', i, ': ', loss_value)
        x += step * grad_values
    
    return x

DeepDream also requires a list of scales (or octaves) at which to process the images. Each successive scale is 40% larger than the previous one. In each scale, we run gradient ascent to maximize the loss and then upscale the resulting image by 40%. We then reinject the lost details (drawn from the original image) back to the upscaled version. To start, we'll define some auxillary functions that will help with the future analysis.

In [11]:
def resize_img(img, size):
    img = np.copy(img)
    factors = (1, float(size[0]) / img.shape[1], float(size[1]) / img.shape[2], 1)
    return scipy.ndimage.zoom(img, factors, order=1)

def save_img(img, fname):
    pil_img = deprocess_image(np.copy(img))
    #scipy.misc.imsave(fname, pil_img)
    imageio.imwrite(fname, pil_img)

# formats picture into tensor that a convnet can process
def preprocess_image(image_path):
    img = image.load_img(image_path)
    img = image.img_to_array(img)
    img = np.expand_dims(img, axis=0)
    img = inception_v3.preprocess_input(img)
    return img

# util function to convert tensor into a valid image
def deprocess_image(x):
    if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
        x = x.reshape((3, x.shape[2], x.shape[3]))
        x = x.transpose((1, 2, 0))
    else:
        x = x.reshape((x.shape[1], x.shape[2], 3))
        
    # undoes preprocessing that is performed by convnet
    x /= 2.
    x += 0.5
    x *= 255.
    x = np.clip(x, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
    return x

Given the auxilary functions, we can now implement DeepDream.

In [12]:
# DeepDream Hyperparameters
step = 0.01  # gradient ascent step size
num_octave = 3  # number of scales at which to run gradient ascent
octave_scale = 1.4  # size ratio between scales
iterations = 20  # number of ascent steps to run at each scale
max_loss = 10.

base_image_path = '/home/d869321/Data/CatsVsDogsSmall/creative_commons_elephant.jpg'  # image to deepdream
#base_image_path = '/home/d869321/Data/CatsVsDogsSmall/train/dogs/dog.6.jpg'
img = preprocess_image(base_image_path)  # loads base image into numpy array

# prepare a list of shape tuples defining the different scales at which to run gradient descent
original_shape = img.shape[1:3]
successive_shapes = [original_shape]
for i in range(1, num_octave):
    shape = tuple([int(dim / (octave_scale ** i)) for dim in original_shape])
    successive_shapes.append(shape)
    
successive_shapes = successive_shapes[::-1]  # reverses the list of tuples so now in increasing order

original_img = np.copy(img)
shrunk_original_img = resize_img(img, successive_shapes[0])  # resizes image to smallest scale

for shape in successive_shapes:
    print('Processing image shape ', shape)
    img = resize_img(img, shape)  # scales us the dream image
    # runs gradient ascent to add dream elements to image
    img = gradient_ascent(img, iterations=iterations, step=step, max_loss=max_loss)
    upscaled_shrunk_original_img = resize_img(shrunk_original_img, shape)  # scales up smaller version
    same_size_original = resize_img(original_img, shape)  # converts original image to same scale as dream
    lost_detail = same_size_original - upscaled_shrunk_original_img
    
    img += lost_detail  # reinjects lost detail into dream
    shrunk_original_img = resize_img(original_img, shape)
    save_img(img, fname='/home/d869321/PycharmProjects/neuralExamples/DeepDreamImages/elephants_deepdream.jpg')
    #save_img(img, fname='/home/d869321/PycharmProjects/neuralExamples/DeepDreamImages/dog_deepdream.jpg')

3. Neural style transfer¶

In a convnet, we expect the high layers to represent the content of an image whilst the earlier layers will contain more local information and hence represent the style of an image. We can thus seek to generate an image whose content is similar to one image (the target_image), but whose style is similar to another image (the style_reference_image) using the following loss:

loss = distance(style(style_reference_image) - style(generated_image))
     + distance(content(target_image) - content(generated_image))

We follow the following steps:

  • set up a network that calulates VGG19 layer activations for the style_reference_image, the target_image and the generated image
  • use the layer activations computed over these three images to define the loss
  • use gradient descent to vary the generated image in order to minimize this loss function

Let us start by defining the paths to the style-reference image and the target image.

In [15]:
from keras.preprocessing.image import load_img, img_to_array
from keras.applications import vgg19
In [16]:
#target_image_path = '/home/d869321/Data/CatsVsDogsSmall/dog.23.jpg'
target_image_path = '/home/d869321/Data/CatsVsDogsSmall/creative_commons_elephant.jpg'
style_reference_image_path = '/home/d869321/Data/CatsVsDogsSmall/1-style.jpg'

# make generated image mantain same aspect ratio as original, but have width 400px
width, height = load_img(target_image_path).size
img_height = 400
img_width = int(width * img_height / height)

We need some auxillary functions that load, preprocess and postprocess the images that go in and out of the convnet.

In [17]:
def preprocess_image(image_path):
    img = load_img(image_path, target_size=(img_height, img_width))
    img = img_to_array(img)
    img = np.expand_dims(img, axis=0)
    img = vgg19.preprocess_input(img)
    return img

def deprocess_image(x):
    # reverse a transformation done by vgg19.preprocess_input
    x[:, :, 0] += 103.939
    x[:, :, 1] += 116.779
    x[:, :, 2] += 123.68
    
    x = x[:, :, ::-1]  # convert image from 'BGR' to 'RGB' (part of reversal of vgg preprocessing)
    x = np.clip(x, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
    return x

We setup the VGG19 network to take as input three images: the style-reference image, the target image and a placeholder that will contain the generated image.

In [18]:
target_image = K.constant(preprocess_image(target_image_path))
style_reference_image = K.constant(preprocess_image(style_reference_image_path))
combination_image = K.placeholder((1, img_height, img_width, 3))  # placeholder for generated image

input_tensor = K.concatenate([target_image, style_reference_image, combination_image], axis=0)

model = vgg19.VGG19(input_tensor=input_tensor, weights='imagenet', include_top=False)  # use convolution base
print('Model loaded.')

Model loaded.

At this point, the neural network will show the activations for the target_image, the style_reference_image and the combination_image. We need to define a loss that we minimize by altering the combination_image.

We start by defining the content loss and style loss (this will requre an auxilary function to compute the Gram matrix of the input). The content loss will use only the upper layer of the convolutional base (block5_conv2) whilst the style loss will use a list of layers that span both low-level and high-level layers.

In [19]:
# define the content loss. base = target_image, combination = generated image
def content_loss(base, combination):
    return K.sum(K.square(combination - base))

# compute Gram matrix of x. This will map the correlations found in x.
def gram_matrix(x):
    features = K.batch_flatten(K.permute_dimensions(x, (2, 0, 1)))  # moves the nFilter dimension to be first
    gram = K.dot(features, K.transpose(features))  # results in a nFilter x nFilter matrix
    return gram

# define style loss. style = style reference image. combination = generated image
def style_loss(style, combination):
    S = gram_matrix(style)
    C = gram_matrix(combination)
    channels = 3
    size = img_height * img_width
    return K.sum(K.square(S - C)) / (4. * (channels ** 2) * (size ** 2))

We also define the total variation loss, which operates on the pixels of the generated image. This loss will encourages spatial continuity in the generated image.

In [20]:
def total_variation_loss(x):
    a = K.square(x[:, :img_height - 1, :img_width - 1, :] - x[:, 1:, :img_width - 1, :])
    b = K.square(x[:, :img_height - 1, :img_width - 1, :] - x[:, :img_height - 1, 1:, :])
    return K.sum(K.pow(a + b, 1.25))

We then minimize a weighted average of these three losses.

In [21]:
outputs_dict = dict([(layer.name, layer.output) for layer in model.layers])  # dict maps layers to activations
content_layer = 'block5_conv2'  # upper-most layer
style_layers = ['block1_conv1', 'block2_conv1', 'block3_conv1', 'block4_conv1', 'block5_conv1']
# define weights for three loss components
total_variation_weight = 1e-4
style_weight = 1.
content_weight = 0.025

# add the content loss
loss = K.variable(0.)  # we'll add all loss components to this variable
layer_features = outputs_dict[content_layer]
# note first dimension of layer_features tells if target_image, style_reference_image or combination_image
target_image_features = layer_features[0, :, :, :]  # dim = (which image?, xAxis, yAxis, numFeatureMaps)
combination_features = layer_features[2, :, :, :]
loss = loss + content_weight * content_loss(target_image_features, combination_features)

# adds the style loss for each specified layer
for layer_name in style_layers:
    layer_features = outputs_dict[layer_name]
    style_reference_features = layer_features[1, :, :, :]
    combination_features = layer_features[2, :, :, :]
    sl = style_loss(style_reference_features, combination_features)
    loss = loss + (style_weight / len(style_layers)) * sl

# adds the variation loss
loss = loss + total_variation_weight * total_variation_loss(combination_image)

We shall perform gradient descent using the L-BFGS algorithm. It comes packaged with SciPy, but it can only applied to flat vectors (instead of the 3D images we are using). In addition, SciPy insists that the value of the loss and the value of the gradient be passed as two separate functions. To bypass this inefficiency, we setup an Evaluator class to calculate the loss and gradient at once. This class shall return the loss when called whilst caching the gradient for the next call.

In [22]:
grads = K.gradients(loss, combination_image)[0]  # gradient of generated image wrt loss
fetch_loss_and_grads = K.function([combination_image], [loss, grads])  # fn to fetch values of loss, grad

# class will wrap fetch_loss_and_grads so that losses and grads can be retrieved via 2 separate method calls
class Evaluator(object):
    
    def __init__(self):
        self.loss_value = None
        self.grads_values = None
        
    def loss(self, x):
        assert self.loss_value is None
        x = x.reshape((1, img_height, img_width, 3))
        outs = fetch_loss_and_grads([x])
        loss_value = outs[0]
        grad_values = outs[1].flatten().astype('float64')
        self.loss_value = loss_value
        self.grad_values = grad_values
        return self.loss_value
    
    def grads(self, x):
        assert self.loss_value is not None
        grad_values = np.copy(self.grad_values)
        self.loss_value = None
        self.grad_values = None
        return grad_values
    
evaluator = Evaluator()

We can now run gradient-ascent using SciPy's L_BFGS algorithm.

In [23]:
from scipy.optimize import fmin_l_bfgs_b

result_prefix = 'NeuralTransferImages/my_result'
iterations = 20

x = preprocess_image(target_image_path)  # the initial state x is set to target image
x = x.flatten()  # algorithm can only process flat vectors
for i in range(iterations):
    print('Start of iteration ', i)
    start_time = time.time()
    # run L-BFGS over pixels of generated image to minimize the loss. Note loss and grad passed separately
    x, min_val, info = fmin_l_bfgs_b(evaluator.loss, x, fprime=evaluator.grads, maxfun=20)
    print('Current loss value: ', min_val)
    img = x.copy().reshape((img_height, img_width, 3))
    img = deprocess_image(img)
    
    # save the image
    fname = result_prefix + '_at_iteration_%d.png' % i
    imageio.imwrite(fname, img)
    
    print('Image saved as ', fname)
    end_time = time.time()
    print('Iteration %d completed in %ds' % (i, end_time - start_time))

4. Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs)¶

GANs are an alternative to VAEs for learning latent space of images. A GAN consists of a generator network that takes a vector from the latent space and decodes it into a synthetic image and a discriminator network, which takes an input and predicts whether it is real or was produced by the generator network. The training continues until the discriminator network can't tell the difference between the real and synthetic images.

The GAN chains the generator and discriminator together: gan(x) = discriminator(generator(x)) where x is a sampled point from the latent space. The discriminator is trained using a mix of real/synthetic images together with their label. The discriminator is trained to minimize the binary_crossentropy whilst the generator attempts to maximize the binary_crossentropy.

The optimization minimum isn't fixed as the loss landscape changes as the two networks are updated. This makes GANs notoriously difficult to train. Here are some tricks:

  • use tanh as the last activation of the generator (instead of sigmoid)
  • sample points from the latent space using a normal distribution (instead of a uniform distribution)
  • add randomness by firstly using dropout in the discriminator and secondly adding random noise to the labels of the discriminator
  • Though sparse gradients are helpful for most forms of deeplearning, they hurt GANs. Thus, instead of max pooling, use a strided convolution for downsampling and use a LeakyReLU activation (which enables small negative values) instead of a ReLU activation.
  • ensure the kernel size is divisible by the stride size when using Conv2DTranspose (for image upsampling) or Conv2D in both networks.

We shall apply a GAN to CIFAR10, a dataset of 50,000 32xx32 RGB images belonging to 10 classes (5,000 images per class). TO make things easier, we'll focus on the frog class.

4.1. The Generator¶

The generator may get stuck with synthetic images that look like noise. Often applying dropout to both networks helps to avoid this.

In [26]:
latent_dim = 32

4.3. The Adversarial Network¶

We now chain the generator and the discriminator. When training gan, we wish to freeze the training of the discriminator.

In [29]:
discriminator.trainable = False  # dont want to train the discriminator within the GAN. Focus on generator.

gan_input = keras.Input(shape=(latent_dim,))
gan_output = discriminator(generator(gan_input))
gan = keras.models.Model(gan_input, gan_output)

gan_optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.0004, clipvalue=1.0, decay=1e-8)
gan.compile(optimizer=gan_optimizer, loss='binary_crossentropy')

4.4 Training the GAN¶

The training loop is as follows:

  1. Draw random points in the latent space
  2. Generate images with generator
  3. Mix the synthetic images with the real ones
  4. Train discriminator using these mixed images and their corresponding labels
  5. Draw new random point in latent space
  6. Train gan with random vectors whose corresponding labels are "real image" As the discriminator is frozen in the gan, only the generator will have its weights updated so that the resulting images are more likely to fool the current discriminator

Let's get the data and normalize it.

In [30]:
(x_train, y_train), (_, _) = keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data()

x_train = x_train[y_train.flatten() == 6]  # select just the frog images
# normalize the images
x_train = x_train.reshape((x_train.shape[0],) + (height, width, channels)).astype('float32') / 255.

We can now train the model.

In [31]:
iterations = 10000
batch_size = 20
save_dir = '/home/d869321/PycharmProjects/neuralExamples/GANImages'

start = 0
for step in range(iterations):
    random_latent_vectors = np.random.normal(size=(batch_size, latent_dim))  # get random pnts in latent space
    
    # generate batch_size images and combine with batch_size real images
    generated_images = generator.predict(random_latent_vectors)  # decodes them to synthetic images
    stop = start + batch_size
    real_images = x_train[start:stop]
    combined_images = np.concatenate([generated_images, real_images])
    labels = np.concatenate([np.ones((batch_size, 1)), np.zeros((batch_size, 1))])  # "0"=real, "1"=fake
    labels += 0.05 * np.random.random(labels.shape)  # important! adding noise helps with training
    
    d_loss = discriminator.train_on_batch(combined_images, labels)  # train the discriminator
    
    random_latent_vectors = np.random.normal(size=(batch_size, latent_dim))  # get random pnts in latent space
    
    misleading_targets = np.zeros((batch_size, 1))  # lie and say all the images generated within GAN are real
    
    a_loss = gan.train_on_batch(random_latent_vectors, misleading_targets)  # train the generator via GAN
    
    # allows us to reprocess the cifar10 images after we have completed a sweep through them
    start += batch_size
    if start > len(x_train) - batch_size:
        start = 0
    
    # saves and plots every 100-th step
    if step % 100 == 0:
        gan.save_weights('gan.h5')
        
        print('discriminator loss: ', d_loss)
        print('adversarial loss: ', a_loss)
        
        # saves one generated image
        img = image.array_to_img(generated_images[0] * 255., scale=False)
        img.save(os.path.join(save_dir, 'generated_frog' + str(step) + '.png'))
        
        # saves one real image for comparison    
        img = image.array_to_img(real_images[0] * 255., scale=False)
        img.save(os.path.join(save_dir, 'real_frog' + str(step) + '.png'))
